AUDIO: 'didn\'t do a full review video on Happy Horse this week cuz it\'s not state-of-the-art. But if you want to test it out, you can sign up on their site for free, and you do get some credits to test it out. So, if you\'re interested, I\'ll link to this main page'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the description below. Also this week we have this new AI called mocap anything version two and it\'s a big step forward in motion capture. In simple terms, this takes a regular video like a person or a creature, pretty much'

[05:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'anything moving and it turns it into clean animation ready skeletons that you can apply to any 3D character. And the key thing here is it works across totally different skeletons. It can be humans or other animals or even'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fictional characters with weird limbs. Now what makes this version special is how it actually does that. Older systems usually split the problem into two steps. First they guess where the joints are like elbows, knees and wings and'

[06:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they try to convert that into rotations using a separate step called inverse kinematics. The problem is the second step isn\'t learnable and it often gets things wrong. You get weird artifacts like joints twisting unnaturally or'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'spinning. So what this system does instead is go fully end to end. It basically learns everything together. It looks at the video, predicts the pose, and directly outputs the final joint rotations all in one unified model. That'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'means it can actually correct itself and optimize for the final animation quality and not just intermediate guesses. And compared to the previous version, version one, which is on the top row, you can clearly see the difference. The'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'old one has jitter and weird joint spinning, whereas this latest version two looks a lot more stable and accurate. So overall, this is a big deal if you care about animation, games, VFX, or even robotics. It removes a ton of'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'manual work and makes Mocap way more flexible. With just one reference video, you can animate pretty much anything. Now, if you scroll up to the top of the page, they have released a GitHub repo. And here it does contain instructions on'

[07:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how to install and run mocap anything version 2. It also includes the script on how you can train this yourself. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also, this week,'

[07:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
