[08:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s way faster than the other models, especially when the context length gets high. In other words, when your prompt gets very long. Anyways, this is just another open- source model to put on your radar. If you\'re interested in'

[08:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also, this week, we have a new AI for anyone into anime image generation. Zanime just dropped. At a high level, they took one of the best open- source image models'

[08:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'out there, Zimage Base, and they fine-tuned it from the ground up on anime images. This isn\'t just a Laura, but a fully trained model designed to handle anime styles, which gives it way more consistency and range. So, here are'

[08:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some examples of images it can generate. It has all the awesome features of Z image being quite tiny and fast at only 6 billion parameters. If you scroll down the page, they even released a smaller'

[09:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'FP8 version, which is only 6 GB in size, so this can fit comfortably with most consumer GPUs. They also released GGFS for users with non-CUDA GPUs. They even made a distilled four-step version, so'

[09:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it only takes four steps to generate an image, which means it usually finishes in seconds. So, this is insanely fast. Anyways, if making anime images is your thing, definitely check out this model.'

[09:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s pretty capable. I\'ll link to this main page in the description below if you\'re interested. Next up, this project is a really interesting shift in how multi- aent AI systems actually work. It\'s called recursive multi-agent'

[09:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'systems. And the idea here is pretty simple. Instead of AI agents talking to each other in text, they collaborate in their own latent space and they loop their thoughts over and over to refine their answers again and again. What'

[09:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exactly does that mean? Well, normally when you have multiple AI agents working together, they pass messages back and forth in just plain text. That\'s slow, expensive, and very inefficient. Every step requires generating words, decoding'

[10:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them, and then rereading them. Well, this system flips that completely. Instead, the agents communicate using their internal representation, also known as their latent thoughts, before they get turned into words. So, this'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takes a problem as input. It runs multiple agents in a loop and only outputs text at the very end. Think of it like a group of experts silently thinking together, refining an idea over multiple rounds and only speaking once'

[10:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they reach the final answer. And this turns out to be pretty huge because staying in latent space, the system gets faster, cheaper, and actually more accurate. We\'re talking about a 2.4x 4x speed up and also 75% fewer tokens used'

[10:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and over an 8% boost in accuracy across benchmarks. You can even chain multiple different agents together like a planner agent, a critic, and a solver agent. So'

[11:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the output of the last agent feeds back into the first and the process repeats again. And what\'s really interesting is that most of these rounds happen silently. There\'s no text generated at all until the final step. And that\'s why it\'s so efficient. Now, they tested this'

[11:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'across a bunch of different setups, including sequential agents, mixture of specialists, and even distillation setups where a smaller model learns from a bigger one. And in pretty much every case, this recursive approach'

[11:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'outperformed standard methods. Here\'s one wild example. On a math problem, for the first round, it gets the answer wrong. But by the second round, the system corrects itself. And by the third round, not only does it get the answer,'

[11:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but it explains it more clearly. So, it\'s not just improving accuracy, it\'s actually refining reasoning over time. And the scaling behavior is also interesting. The deeper you let the system loop, the better it performs.'

[11:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'While traditional textbased systems start to plateau or get even worse, this one just keeps improving. As you can see here, across all these different benchmarks, the more rounds you add, the better its performance. So, why does'

[12:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this matter? Well, this is basically a new way to scale AI. Instead of making models just bigger or adding more data, you just let multiple agents think together and loop that process in hidden'

[12:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'latent space. It\'s cheaper, faster, and more flexible. And if this direction keeps working, it could become the default way multi- aent AI systems are built going forward. The awesome thing is at the top of the page, they\'ve'

[12:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already released the models and the code to this. So, if you click on this code button and you scroll down a bit here, it contains all the instructions on how to download and run this locally on your computer. If you\'re interested in'

[12:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Next up, this AI is also pretty cool. It\'s called Vista 4D, and this lets you take a normal video and turn it into a 4D scene. In other words, everything is in'

[12:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D with the element of time. Here are some other examples for your reference. And this means that you can also reshoot the scene using any camera movement or angle you want. So this is a super flexible tool. Here are some other'

[13:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'examples for your reference. You can see that here we can even do some really cool zoom parallax effects like this. And you know all the characters and all the details from the original video stay consistent the entire time. Now, if you'

[13:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'compare this generation from Vista 4D to other 4D generators like Recam Master or Trajectory Crafter, which I\'ve gone over on my channel before, you can see that by far Vista 4D is the most coherent and'

[13:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the most accurate. Here\'s another example for your reference. It\'s able to keep the details of the character and everything else consistent throughout the generation. Now, the really cool thing is because it essentially converts'

[13:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this into a 3D point cloud, you can then edit the point cloud however you want and then reconstruct that into a video. For example, in the top row, the source video only has one car, but we can add'

[14:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an extra car to the 3D point cloud and then it would render a video with two cars in the scene. Or here\'s something even crazier. You can even insert an entire video. for example, this old'

[14:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'couple sitting at a bench and then just add that 3D point cloud into the original 3D scene. And now we can merge these two things together. Pretty cool. Or here\'s another example where in the'

[14:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'top row we can choose to completely remove the old man at the front in the 3D scene and afterwards we can rerender this into a new video without this old man. Or alternatively, we can also take this video of a rhino and extract the 3D'

[14:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'point cloud of the rhino and insert that into the 3D scene of the original video and rerender it so that we get the exact rhino walking into the scene. Or here\'s an even cooler example. Now, from the'

[14:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'source video, you can see that this is a fixed point. We don\'t really know what the rest of the room looks like, but after plugging it through Vista 4D, it\'s able to extrapolate and just guess what the sides of the room would look like.'

