[21:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'worth of credits per month and don\'t fully utilize their individual subscriptions. So that\'s how you can access multiple LLMs at such a low cost. Definitely check out Merlin AI using the link in the description below. Also,'

[21:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this week, this project is a really interesting shift in how research itself might work. So, it\'s called the last human written paper, agentnative research artifacts. And here\'s the core idea. In the near future, most computer'

[21:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'science or even just general scientific papers will be written by AI and most will also be read by AI. So, what does that mean and why does it matter? Well, right now a research paper is basically'

[21:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a clean story. What you see published is just the final idea, the methods, and the actual findings that work. But in reality, that\'s not how research actually happens. In reality, it\'s'

[22:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'messy. You try a bunch of different ideas, and most of them fail. You hit weird bugs, you pivot, and finally something works. But all of this gets thrown away when the paper is actually written and published. So this leads to'

[22:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a huge loss of knowledge and this creates two problems. The first one is what they call the storytelling tax. You only see the winning path but you don\'t see the dead ends and the decisions that led there. So there\'s a lot of useful'

[22:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'insight that disappears. They also talk about this engineering tax. And here\'s the idea behind it. Papers don\'t include enough detail to actually reproduce work. Things like hyperparameters and fixes are often missing. So anyone'

[22:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trying to rebuild the system basically has to rediscover everything by themselves from scratch. Again, all of this is just lost knowledge. But here\'s the solution. So they call this the agent native research artifacts or ARRA'

[22:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for short. Think of it like this. Instead of a PDF research paper with just an abstract, introduction, methods, results, etc. Here, research becomes a structured package that\'s readable by'

[23:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI. So here\'s what the structure looks like. You still have a human readable overview, but you also have the actual logic like claims and experiments, the full code and configs needed to run it.'

[23:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You also have a complete graph of the research process including failed attempts and all the raw evidence like logs and results. So instead of a polished story, you get the entire'

[23:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trajectory. And here\'s the interesting part. This isn\'t something that researchers have to manually write. They also introduce a system called the live research manager. And this captures everything automatically while you work.'

[23:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Every experiment, every failure, every tweak, it\'s all recorded in the background automatically by this agent. So over time, this artifact basically builds itself. And in terms of results,'

[23:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this actually helps AI systems learn a lot. It improves understanding. It makes reproducing the experiment way easier. And it even helps with extending the research further. So the big idea here'

[24:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a shift from narrative to knowledge. Instead of compressing research into just a boring polished scientific PDF that humans can read, now you can store the full research process so that both humans and AI can actually use it. And'

