[37:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also, this week, this is actually a really fascinating idea. It\'s called Talkie. And this is a 13 billion parameter model that only knows the world up to 1930. In other words,'

[38:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re not talking to a modern AI trained on the internet. You\'re talking to something that\'s been trained entirely on historical stuff like books, newspapers, basically anything up to 1930. And here\'s why it matters. Pretty'

[38:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much every modern AI you\'ve used, whether it\'s ChatGpt or Claude or Gemini, they\'ve all been trained on basically the same thing, the modern internet. Even when these models feel different, maybe you get a different'

[38:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vibe from each of them, they\'re still kind of related because they\'re all just trained on the same data. A vintage model like this lets researchers ask a very fundamental question. How much of what we think we know about AI is just'

[38:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tied to the specific training data set. If we train a model on something completely different, you finally start to see what\'s going on under the hood. Here\'s one of the interesting experiments they ran. They took thousands of on this day historical'

[38:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'events from the New York Times and measured how surprising these events are to talk. So events from before 1930 feel normal to it because well that\'s part of its training data. But once you cross'

[39:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the knowledge cutoff its surprise jumps up especially in the \' 50s and60s. If you tell it about events that happened during that time it gets pretty surprised but then it kind of plateaus. Even from 2000 and beyond it doesn\'t'

[39:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really get surprised any further. What\'s interesting here is you can literally watch the model react to history. It has no way of knowing. They also ran a coding experiment. They gave this vintage model a Python coding test. Now,'

[39:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this model has never seen a computer. It has no concept of what Python is. And they showed it a few example Python functions in the prompt and said, "Okay, write a new one." And it actually got'

[39:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some right. Not a lot and only really simple ones, but think about what that means. The model has no idea what code is, but it still picked up enough from a few examples to grasp the concept of this function. That\'s a real'

[40:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generalization signal, and it\'s a clean one because there\'s zero contamination. The model literally has never seen Python code or this answer before during training. Here\'s another really interesting test. They compared Taki to'

[40:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a modern twin. This model was trained on data up until now, which is the gray bar on these charts. You can see that Taki does lose on knowledge tests, which makes more sense because it doesn\'t know modern stuff. But on core language'

[40:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understanding and basic numerousy, it holds up surprisingly well. The team thinks the remaining gap is mostly because of data quality issues, especially OCR. Since none of the text in its training data was digital, all of'

[40:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it had to be like scanned and transcribed from physical pages, often with very messy handwriting. And during that process, a lot of these words got mangled. For example, its training data looks something like this with a lot of'

[40:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'spelling errors. So those are some of their key findings. They\'re already training a larger model that\'s coming out this summer. They also want to expand beyond English and also redo a chunk of the OCR with their new system so the training data is more accurate.'

[41:08] [scene:talk]
